SIMPLE: shrift
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Shrift
<hw>Shrift</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>shrift</ets>,
<ets>schrift</ets>, AS. <ets>scrift</ets>, fr. <ets>scr⟦imac⟧fan</ets>
to shrive. See <er>Shrive</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of
shriving.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In <qex>shrift</qex> and preaching is my diligence.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Confession made to a priest, and the absolution
consequent upon it.</def> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Have you got leave to go to <qex>shrift</qex> to-day?</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Therefore, my lord, address you to your <qex>shrift</qex>,⟦br⟧
And be yourself; for you must die this instant.</q>
<rj><qau>Rowe.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Shrift father</b></col>, <cd>a priest to whom confession
is made.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shright</ent>⟦br⟧
